SIMPLE: overhead
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Overhead
<hw>O`ver*head"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>Aloft; above; in
or attached to the ceiling or roof; in the story or upon the floor
above; in the zenith.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>While <qex>overhead</qex> the moon⟦br⟧
Sits arbitress.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>Also used adjectively; as, an <xex>overhead</xex> crane, gear,
etc.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Overhead engine</b></col>, <cd>a vertical steam engine in
which the cylinder stands above the crank.</cd> -- <col><b>Overhead
work</b></col>, <cd>a general term in manufactories for countershafting
and gearing, when overhead.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>overhead</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: overhead
<hw>o"ver*head`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>same
as <er>overhead expenses</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A compartment on a train, bus, or airplane used for
storage of luggage or accessory equipment; called also <ecol><b>overhead
compartment</b></ecol>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Sports)</fld> <def>A stroke with a racket in which
the ball is struck with the racket over the head, moving in a downward
motion; also called <ecol><b>overhead stroke</b></ecol>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Overhead expenses</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Overhead charges</ent>⟦br⟧
